  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the symptoms of eczema?",
  "response": "Eczema, also known as atopic dermatitis, is a chronic skin condition characterized by inflammation, itching, and rash. Symptoms can vary in severity and presentation but often include:\n\n### Common Symptoms:\n1. **Itching (Pruritus):**\n   - Intense itching is the hallmark of eczema and can be severe, often worse at night.\n   \n2. **Dry Skin:**\n   - The skin may appear dry, scaly, or rough.\n\n3. **Red or Inflamed Skin:**\n   - Affected areas may become red, swollen, and irritated.\n\n4. **Rash:**\n   - A rash can develop, often in patches, and may appear on the face, hands, elbows, knees, or other parts of the body.\n\n5. **Cracking or Thickened Skin:**\n   - Chronic eczema can lead to thickened, leathery skin (lichenification) or cracking.\n\n6. **Oozing or Crusting:**\n   - In some cases, the skin may ooze clear fluid and form crusts, especially if scratched.\n\n7. **Sensitive Skin:**\n   - The skin may become more sensitive to irritants, allergens, or changes in weather.\n\n### Additional Symptoms in Infants:\n- **Cheeks, Scalp, and Body:** Eczema in infants often appears on the cheeks, scalp, and body.\n- **Crying and Irritability:** Due to discomfort and itching.\n\n### Flare-Up Triggers:\n- **Allergens:** Pollen, pet dander, dust mites.\n- **Irritants:** Soaps, detergents, synthetic fabrics.\n- **Climate:** Cold, dry weather or excessive sweating.\n- **Stress:** Emotional stress can worsen symptoms.\n- **Infections:** Bacterial or viral infections can trigger flare-ups.\n\n### When to See a Doctor:\n- If symptoms persist despite over-the-counter treatments.\n- If there are signs of infection (e.g., pus, increased redness, fever).\n- If eczema significantly impacts daily life or sleep.\n\nProper diagnosis and treatment by a healthcare provider, often a dermatologist, are essential for managing eczema effectively. Treatment may include moisturizers, topical corticosteroids, antihistamines, and lifestyle changes to avoid triggers.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
